			<h3>Prompt</h3>
			<p>For this design exercise, I chose prompt #3 Garage Sale Helper and am taking the lo-fi product overview approach. I chose this approach because it seemed like building any sort of high-fidelity mockup would be putting the cart before the horse. There were so many other high-level things to think about in this application that it didn’t seem right to jump straight into designing a specific screen, especially in detail.
			</p>
			
			<h3>Talking to Users</h3>
			<p>The very first thing I did was find a couple of potential users to talk to and learn from. This felt like the right place to start because I really didn’t know much about the problem and users' specific pain points.</p>
			<p>I started by finding a garage sale (via Craigslist) this past Sunday and talking to the host, David, about his experience setting up the sale and running it for the previous few days. Here are some of the takeaways from that conversation:</p>
			<ul>
				<li>He definitely would not want to inventory every single item (would be <em>extremely</em> tedious).</li>
				<li>Pricing items is difficult. He was afraid of pricing items too low and not getting what they're actually worth. For example, he claimed that the King James Bible audio cassette tape set he was selling was going for $50 online, but he never would have guessed without specifically checking.</li>
				<li>The biggest help would be to actually get people in the door. A lot of people drive by thinking there isn't much there, but they might not be seeing everything.</li>
				<li>He only posted his sale on Craigslist, but some of his customers claimed they found him through other apps/sites.</li>
			</ul>
			<p>It was interesting and eye opening to talk to David about his garage sale hosting experience. I definitely didn’t expect some of the pain points he expressed, and was happy to hear some of his ideas on how the experience could be improved.</p>
			<figure>
				<a href="/google/david-g-sale.jpg"><img src="/google/david-g-sale.jpg" alt="A photo of David's garage sale. There were more items out back on the deck."></a>
