			<p>The next step was to get a buyer’s perspective. My Uncle Marty is a garage sale extraordinaire and ended up having some great insight on the garage sale shopping experience (I feel like this could be called “garage sailing”). Here are some takeaways from that conversation:
			</p>
			<ul>
				<li>There is a big difference between garage sales, moving sales, and estate sales.</li>
				<li>His main resource for finding sales is online – primarily Craigslist, but there are other services as well.</li>
				<li>Garage sales may tend to happen on different days of the week depending on where you live. In Chardon (near Cleveland), Marty says that Thursday, Friday, and Saturday are the most popular garage sale days.</li>
				<li>Sometimes, Marty shows up at sales listed on Craigslist to find that they don’t exist or aren’t happening for whatever reason. He has learned to trust Craigslist ads less than newspaper ads because people pay for newspaper ads and are that much more committed to actually having the sale.</li>
				<li>The night before he goes out to garage sales, he looks up ads and plans a route to hit a handful of them in a single day</li>
				<li>Some hosts allow “early birds” while others are very strict about the hours they are open.</li>
				<li>Sale listings usually include high-level categories (e.g. “antiques”) that might hint at some of the items at the sale, but rarely are the ads much more specific</li>
				<li>He’s often skeptical of ad descriptions. The best sales are often the ones with the least written about them.</li>
				<li>If a host has much left over after a sale, “buyout people" might offer to buy the remainder of the items for pennies on the dollar.</li>
			</ul>
			<p>Marty's input taught me a lot about the process of finding the best garage/moving/estate sales, and was helpful as I referenced it throughout the project.</p>

			<h3>Mind Map of Buyer and Seller experiences</h3>
			<p>My next step was to synthesize these conversations into something visual that could help me identify pain points and think about the buying and selling experiences as a whole. What came out was sort of a mind map that outlined each of these processes at a high level. They aren’t pretty, but they were useful in getting some of my first thoughts down on paper.
			</p>
