			<h3>Platform and Features</h3>
			<p>At this point, I felt like I was ready to decide on a platform for this product. Given the suggestions and use cases discussed with my potential users, I ultimately landed on a native mobile app. Some of the reasons included having the ability to access the built-in camera for sellers creating listings, route planning/navigation for buyers out shopping, and push notifications for various potential features.
			</p>
			<p>As I started thinking through design solutions for this mobile app, a lot of features were coming to mind – way too many features for a version one. If this were a real project, it would be important to define an MVP at this point and be specific about what we wanted it to prove. Here are some of the features I immediately identified as extraneous for a first version:
			</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Alerts (push notification/email/SMS) based on saved search criteria</li>
				<li>Ratings (buyers get a push notification when they leave a sale, asking them to rate it)</li>
				<li>Pricing helper (helps determine pricing by comparing to other items in the area, eBay or other places online)</li>
			</ul>	

